external.description:
A recent breach of the U.S. federal court filing system has been attributed to Russian government hackers, according to sources. The attackers reportedly exploited this access to spy on mid-level criminal cases, particularly in the New York City region and other jurisdictions. The targeted system is likely PACER (Public Access to Court Electronic Records), a critical repository of legal documents used by courts, attorneys, and the public.

This incident underscores significant risks to national security and judicial integrity. Access to criminal case details could provide foreign adversaries with insights into ongoing investigations, law enforcement tactics, and sensitive personal information. The breach highlights the need for robust cybersecurity measures in government systems, particularly those handling sensitive legal data.

From a technical standpoint, the breach may have been facilitated through phishing, unpatched vulnerabilities, or credential theft. The attribution to Russian state-sponsored actors suggests a targeted espionage operation, aligning with historical patterns of Russian cyber activities. However, attribution in cyber incidents remains complex and requires thorough forensic analysis.

For cybersecurity professionals, this incident reinforces the importance of continuous monitoring, multi-factor authentication, and Zero Trust architectures in critical infrastructure. Organizations handling sensitive legal data must prioritize threat detection and response capabilities to mitigate such risks.

external.description: Google has implemented a new policy requiring developers of cryptocurrency wallet and exchange applications to obtain government licenses before publishing their apps in 15 jurisdictions. This initiative aims to foster a safer and more compliant ecosystem for users. The regions impacted by this policy include Bahrain, Canada, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Israel, Japan, the Philippines, South Africa, South Korea, Switzerland, and Thailand, among others. The FBI's recent report of $9.9 million in losses due to scams highlights the critical need for such regulations. By mandating government licenses, Google is taking a significant step towards mitigating fraudulent activities and enhancing user trust in the crypto space. From a technical perspective, this policy ensures that only licensed and presumably vetted apps are available on the Google Play Store. Licensed apps are more likely to adhere to security best practices, reducing the risk of hacks and scams. This move could significantly reduce the number of malicious apps on the platform. The impact on the cybersecurity landscape is substantial. This policy could set a precedent for other tech giants to follow, leading to a more secure and regulated environment for crypto transactions. It also signals a growing recognition of the need for regulatory oversight in the crypto space. For developers, this means ensuring they have the necessary licenses before publishing their apps. While this might increase the barrier to entry, it will also enhance the credibility of their apps. Users will benefit from a safer ecosystem where apps have been vetted and licensed, reducing the risk of falling victim to scams. For regulators, this move aligns with the growing trend of regulatory oversight in the crypto space, which could lead to more standardized and secure practices across the industry. In conclusion, Google's new policy is a positive step towards creating a safer and more compliant ecosystem for cryptocurrency transactions. It highlights the importance of regulatory oversight and sets a precedent for other platforms to follow.

external.description:

この成功により、事前登録達成時の豪華報酬や抽選プレゼント企画が確定し、声優のサイン色紙やゲーム内アイテムの追加配布が行われます。

「オズリラ」は、現代文明と異世界を融合させた独自の世界観とアニメ調のキャラクター、深い絆を育む交流要素が特徴で、豪華声優のフルボイスによる物語や美麗なアニメーションシーンを楽しめます。  
8月19日に配信予定で、基本無料のアイテム課金制となるこのゲームは、iOS・Android対応で、日本公式SNSや公式サイトから詳細情報や事前登録が可能です。  
今後も目標達成を目指して多くのユーザーの参加を呼びかけており、新作アプリゲームのトップに注目されています。

Intellectual loneliness isn't about wanting
'deep talks. It's about realising how few people can tolerate complexity. It's noticing how quickly people rush to have an answer not to understand, but to feel right. It's watching people form entire worldviews off headlines, vibes, and whatever reels told them last. It's the silence that follows when you say something that doesn't fit neatly into someone's script. It's not arrogance. It's exhaustion, from always having to code-switch between what you actually think and what's safe to say around people who shut down at nuance. And no one warns you:
Once your brain learns to stretch, small talk doesn't just bore you, it alienates you. You're not looking for smart people. You're looking for people who are still thinking.

This is an HST image OH231.8+4.2, also known as the Calabash Nebula (credit: NASA/ESA & Valentin Bujarrabal ). It is a dying star, that has ejected most of its mass into interstellar space. It will eventually form a planetary nebula. Because it contains unusually large amounts of sulfur, it's also called the 'Rotten Egg Nebula'. These protoplanetary nebulae are very rare objects because of their very short lifetimes.

value.text: Polari prize update: John Boyne has now made a statement. I'm putting it below.

images.alt:
For 6 years, since the publication of My Brother's Name is Jessica I've been the focus of an extraordinary amount of bullying and intimidation not just at the hands of trans activists but also by a small group of toxic novelists

My views on trans rights have never changed and they're quite simple: All human beings should have the same rights, but if the rights of trans women come into conflict with the rights of what you call 'cis' women, then the latter must take precedence. There's 4 billion of them, after all, and it took them 2,000 years to achieve even a semblance of equality. That's pretty much my only thoughts on the subject

To the organisers and judges of the Polari Prize: thank you for standing strong in the face of extraordinary intimidation

To the writers who withdrew from the prize and those who organised petitions, I say this: You may have meant well. You may have thought you were doing an honourable thing. But you forgot one crucial fact. That the novelist you're protesting, and the novel you tried to exclude, is part of a sequence about sexual abuse from a gay man who endured that very trauma at school, was denied justice because my abuser died in the months leading up to the trial, and is still coping with not getting my day in court. And how do I cope?

When I published my debut novel in 2000, I would have given my left arm to find myself on a prize list. The attention it brings to a new writer - or, more importantly - a writer's work is terrific. You sell more copies, your publisher starts thinking about your next contract, and you get to continue doing the job you love. It seems absurd and wrong to me that so many debut writers are losing their opportunity for this either through misguided ideas about who I am or as I'm aware has happened in some cases because you too were bullied or intimated into withdrawing. I love fiction I love literature and I've always supported new writers through reviews and blurbs so this and this alone weighs on me.

So, I propose the following. I have shelves full of awards at home and my book sales are extremely healthy. I would encourage all the debut writers on the Polari Longlist to return to the list, to look forward to the shortlist announcement and, in time, the fun and excitement of the ceremony. One of you gets to win the prize, and that's as it should be. The organisers stood firm and didn't expel me from the longlist, which I appreciated. And I am not withdrawing from the longlist. However, should the debut writers all return, I would respectfully ask the judges not to consider Earth for the shortlist. I don't think I can say any fairer than that.

I came very close to the edge this week because of endless harassment at the hands of both strangers and fellow writers. I remained silent throughout but there's been a few moments where I thought it would be easier not to go on. There's really only so much abuse one person can take. However, I'm still here. Because I have too many books in me that I still want to write. And so do all of you.

The Elements, the combined edition of the novellas Water, Earth, Fire, and Air, will be published on September 9th in the US and September 25th in the UK and Ireland. I hope you get a chance to read it. I'm very proud of the book. But then I'm proud of all my books and of the fact that I've spent my 33-year career helping other writers, elevating them, and finding opportunities to promote them, rather than trying to tear them down.

Online bullying has has to stop.
John Boyne
